  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the difference between L1 and L2 regularization? When does each perform better?",
  "response_text": "L1 and L2 regularization are techniques used to prevent overfitting in machine learning models by adding a penalty term to the loss function. The main differences between them lie in how they penalize the weights of the model.\n\n**L1 Regularization (Lasso Regression):**\n- **Penalty Term:** L1 regularization adds the absolute value of the magnitude of coefficients as a penalty term to the loss function.\n- **Effect on Weights:** This can lead to some feature weights being reduced to exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection.\n- **Use Case:** It is particularly useful when you want to reduce the number of features in your model or when you have a large number of features and you suspect that only a few of them are important.\n\n**L2 Regularization (Ridge Regression):**\n- **Penalty Term:** L2 regularization adds the square of the magnitude of coefficients as a penalty term to the loss function.\n- **Effect on Weights:** This tends to shrink the coefficients but does not set them to zero, meaning it keeps all features in the model.\n- **Use Case:** It is beneficial when you have multicollinearity among predictors (i.e., when predictor variables are highly correlated) because it spreads the error among all the predictors.\n\nIn summary, L1 regularization is more effective for feature selection and can be used when you want to simplify the model by reducing the number of features, while L2 regularization is better suited for handling multicollinearity and when you want to keep all features in the model.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
